SIMPLE: apse
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Apse
<hw>Apse</hw> <pr>(⟦acr⟧ps)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
Apses</plu> <pr>(⟦acr⟧p"s⟦ecr⟧z)</pr>. [See <er>Apsis</er>.] <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Arch.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A projecting part of a building,
esp. of a church, having in the plan a polygonal or semicircular
termination, and, most often, projecting from the east end. In early
churches the Eastern apse was occupied by seats for the bishop and
clergy.</def> Hence: <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The bishop's seat or throne, in
ancient churches.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A reliquary, or case in which the relics of saints
were kept.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This word is also written <asp>apsis</asp> and
<asp>absis</asp>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Apsidal</ent>⟦br⟧
